ellectual factors behind the formation of cheap print collections, how these collections were used by their owners, and what this activity can tell us about 'print culture' in the early modern period. The book's central collector is John Bagford (1650-1715), a shoemaker who became a dealer of prints and other 'curiosities' to important collectors of the time such as Samuel Pepys, Hans Sloane and Robert Harley. Bagford's own rich and largely unstudied collection is afascinating study in its own right and his position at the centre of commercial and intellectual networks opens up a whole world of collecting. This world encompasses later Stuart partisan political culture, when modern parties and the 'public sphere' first emerged; the 'New Science' and 'virtuoso culture' with its milieu of natural philosophers, antiquaries and artisans; the aural and visual landscape of marketplaces, streets and alehouses; and developing practices of record-keeping, life-writing and historical writing during the long eighteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPrinted ephemeraxCollectors and collectingzGreat Britain. 0aPrinted ephemeraxHistoryy17th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aPrinted ephemerazGreat BritainxHistoryy17th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / Georgian Era (1714-1837).2bisacsh  aAntiquarianism.  aBibliophiles.  aCollecting.  aCuriosity.  aLibraries.  aMemory.  aNostalgia.  aPeriodicals.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800104013?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800104013423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800104013/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Comp